4 SECTION 8. IC 35-47-4-6.3 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
5 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
6 1, 2026]: Sec. 6.3. (a) The following definitions apply throughout
7 this section:
8 (1) "Crime of domestic violence" has the meaning set forth in
9 IC 35-31.5-2-78.
10 (2) "Domestic batterer" means a person:
11 (A) who has been convicted of domestic battery (IC
12 35-42-2-1.3) or a crime of domestic violence; and
13 (B) whose right to possess a firearm has not been restored
14 under section 7 of this chapter.
15 (3) "License" means any license or permit to carry a
16 handgun.
17 (4) "Residence" means one (1) or more of the following:
18 (A) The location where a person spends most of the
19 person's time, including a residence owned or leased by
20 another person if the person:
21 (i) does not own or lease a residence; or
22 (ii) spends more time at the residence owned or leased by
23 the other person than at the residence owned or leased
24 by the person.
25 (B) A particular location where a person spends more than
26 three (3) nights in a thirty (30) day period.
27 (5) "Surrender" means to make available for confiscation by
28 a law enforcement agency or law enforcement officer having
29 jurisdiction over one (1) or more of the following:
30 (A) The location of the offense.
31 (B) The location of the defendant's residence at any time
32 between the defendant's arrest and the conclusion of the
33 defendant's sentence.
34 (b) A domestic batterer who knowingly or intentionally fails to
35 surrender any:
36 (1) firearm; or
37 (2) license;
38 owned or possessed by the domestic batterer commits unlawful
39 retention of a firearm or license by a domestic batterer, a Class A
40 misdemeanor. However, the offense is a Level 6 felony if the person
41 has a prior unrelated conviction for an offense under this section.
42 (c) It is a defense to a prosecution under this section that:
2026 IN 1299—LS 6347/DI 144

4
1 (1) a court did not issue a written order described in section
2 6.4(a) of this chapter before the domestic batterer's failure to
3 surrender any firearm or license owned or possessed by the
4 domestic batterer; or
5 (2) the appropriate law enforcement agency or law
6 enforcement officer failed to confiscate a firearm or license
7 eligible for confiscation under this section in a timely manner.
8 (d) It is not a defense to a prosecution under this section that a
9 firearm or license subject to confiscation by a law enforcement
10 agency or law enforcement officer under this section was in the
11 possession of a third party not specified in the court order
12 described in section 6.4(a) of this chapter.
13 (e) Nothing in this chapter shall be construed to prevent a
14 person who is:
15 (1) the rightful owner of a firearm confiscated under this
16 section; and
17 (2) not otherwise disqualified or prohibited from owning or
18 possessing a firearm under state or federal law;
19 from reclaiming a confiscated firearm from the law enforcement
20 agency or law enforcement officer responsible for originally
21 confiscating the firearm.
22 SECTION 9. IC 35-47-4-6.4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
23 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
24 1, 2026]: Sec. 6.4. (a) A court, upon entering a judgment of
25 conviction for domestic battery or a crime of domestic violence,
26 shall issue a written order that does the following:
27 (1) Prohibits the defendant from owning or possessing a
28 firearm.
29 (2) Requires the defendant to surrender all firearms and
30 licenses owned or possessed by the defendant.
31 (3) Orders an appropriate law enforcement:
32 (A) agency; or
33 (B) officer;
34 to confiscate all firearms and all licenses owned or possessed
35 by the defendant.
36 (4) Advises the defendant of the rights described in section 7
37 of this chapter.
38 (b) A law enforcement agency or law enforcement officer
39 subject to a written court order described in subsection (a) shall
40 comply with subsection (a) not later than seventy-two (72) hours
41 after receipt of the written court order described in subsection (a).
42 SECTION 10. IC 35-47-4-7, AS AMENDED BY P.L.181-2014,
2026 IN 1299—LS 6347/DI 144

5
1 SECTION 18, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
2 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 7. (a) Notwithstanding IC 35-47-2, IC 35-47-2.5,
3 the restoration of the right to serve on a jury under IC 33-28-5-18, the
4 restoration of the right to vote under IC 3-7-13-5, or the expungement
5 of a crime of domestic violence under IC 35-38-9, and except as
6 provided in subsections (b), (c), and (f), a person who has been
7 convicted of a crime of domestic violence may not possess a firearm.
8 (b) Not earlier than five (5) years after the date of conviction, a
9 person who has been convicted of a crime of domestic violence may
10 petition the court for restoration of the person's right to possess a
11 firearm. In determining whether to restore the person's right to possess
12 a firearm, the court shall consider the following factors:
13 (1) Whether the person has been subject to:
14 (A) a protective order;
15 (B) a no contact order;
16 (C) a workplace violence restraining order; or
17 (D) any other court order that prohibits the person from
18 possessing a firearm.
19 (2) Whether the person has successfully completed a substance
20 abuse program, if applicable.
21 (3) Whether the person has successfully completed a parenting
22 class, if applicable.
23 (4) Whether the person still presents a threat to the victim of the
24 crime.
25 (5) Whether there is any other reason why the person should not
26 possess a firearm, including whether the person failed to satisfy
27 a specified condition under subsection (c) or whether the person
28 has committed a subsequent offense.
29 (c) The court may condition the restoration of a person's right to
30 possess a firearm upon the person's satisfaction of specified conditions.
31 (d) If the court denies a petition for restoration of the right to
32 possess a firearm, the person may not file a second or subsequent
33 petition until one (1) year has elapsed after the filing of the most recent
34 petition.
35 (e) A person has not been convicted of a crime of domestic violence
36 for purposes of subsection (a) if the person has been pardoned.
37 (f) The right to possess a firearm shall be restored to a person whose
38 conviction is reversed on appeal or on postconviction review at the
39 earlier of the following:
40 (1) At the time the prosecuting attorney states on the record that
41 the charges that gave rise to the conviction will not be refiled.
42 (2) Ninety (90) days after the final disposition of the appeal or the
2026 IN 1299—LS 6347/DI 144

